default2.3 defaultHow should expendidefaultture on improving safety at level crossings be prioritidefaultseddefault in relation to other demands on the rail budget?default2.3.1 We have no views to express on this difficult issue other than to acknowledge the problem and be thankful that we no longer have to address it
default.  However the situation might be improved if the costs of improving or removing level crossings could be shared by road budgets if the net effect of bridges or underpasses reflected improvements to vehicle and pedestrian flows.
default2.3.2 It might be possible 
defaultfor the provision of basic safety interlockings to be installed in a less costly way by not using expensive high technology solutions.
default2.3.3 Too often assessments for simple procedures produce prohibitive costs to the overall detriment
default of a safe railway.  However, to attempt to now “turn the clock back” is to expose oneself to criticism and being “out of touch”.
default2.4 defaultIs Network Rail giving sufficient priority at level crossings?default2.4.1 
defaultFirstly we accept the historical practices and acknowledge Level Crossings for pedestrians in particular are a difficult area because custom and practice, design and installation has grown up over more than 100 years.  Thus an arrangement in one part of th
defaulte country is different from that in another location particularly with methods of locking wicket gates and other devices.
default2.4.2 The accident at Elsenham in 2005 and more recent examples indicate there is a need for the safe bringing together of systems to 
defaultensure safety is paramount.  The Elsenham case points to a cost cutting 
defaultexercise
default in that only one side of the line was it possible to purchase 
defaulttickets.  Thus the children crossed the line 
defaultto purchase tickets before boarding the train
default 
defaultresulting in their dea
defaultth.
default2.4.3 An in house review of different geographical locations, the history and position of level crossings in those different locations with a view to best procedure would be sensible.
default2.4.4 Network Rail we believe is addressing this problem, details ar
defaulte not 
defaultknown
default to us but we would not 
defaultrecommend the employment of Consultants.  Expertise exists within Network Rail to address the issue which in view 
defaulto
defaultf the different types in existence is a difficult one to address.
default2.4.5 In this context we believe the pre
defaultsent risks model used by the Industry (ORR and NR) called ACRAM (All Level Crossing Risk Model) is flawed in that it covers in great detail road and pedestrian user but pays little attention to Rail levels of traffic, frequency and speed of trains.
default2.5 defaultIs defaultGovernment policy and regulatory action by the Office of Rail Regulation (ORR) in relation to safety and level crossings adequate?  What more should the Government and ORR do?default2.5.1 Care must be taken to ensure there is clear water between the Engineers of
default similar professions employed within each organisation.
default2.5.2 One of the problems arising more and more is the lessening of the role of Railway Operator.  The Engineering culture is paramount and it has been forgotten that traditionally railway safety was 
defaultvested in the Superintendent of the Line, latterly known as the Chief Operating Manager, a qualified operator with the equivalent knowledge comparable with the ticket of a Master Mariner at sea.
default2.5.3 That office had to work with three engi
defaultneering disci
defaultpli
defaultnes, Mechanical and Electrical Engineers, Civil Engineers and Signalling Engineers, all of whom are different and equally important.
default2.5.4 
defaultThat culture has to a great extent has been lost
default.  For example the decision not to provide vital interlocking at More
defaultton on Lugg was taken without any discussions with railway operating experts.  It was also taken without any detailed knowledge on the risks of human error.
default  
defaultWe believe both organisations 
defaulti.e.
default ORR and NR are fit for purpose and have difficult but different
default tasks.
default2.5.5 It is our view
default that operating expertise should reside within NR and not be left to the ORR to pick up.  Historically the industry 
defaultprided itself in its professionalism and felt shame if found wanting  
defaultby the Railway Inspectorate, the predecess
defaultors of the ORR.
